Morocco (/məˈrɒkoʊ/ (listen); Arabic: المغرب‎, romanized: al-maġhrib, lit

Since the foundation of the first Moroccan state by Idris I in 788 AD, the country has been ruled by a series of independent dynasties, reaching its zenith under Almoravid and Almohad rule, when it spanned parts of Iberia and northwestern Africa
Morocco claims the non-self-governing territory of Western Sahara, formerly Spanish Sahara, as its Southern Provinces
The sovereign state is a unitary constitutional monarchy with an elected parliament

Morocco's predominant religion is Islam, and its official languages are Arabic and Berber, the latter achieving official recognition in 2011,[14] having been the native language of Morocco before the Muslim conquest in the seventh century C
Morocco is a member of the Arab League, the Union for the Mediterranean and the African Union
The full Arabic name al-Mamlakah al-Maghribiyyah (المملكة المغربية) translates to "Kingdom of the West"; although "the West" in Arabic is الغرب Al-Gharb
Morocco's English name is based on Marrakesh, its capital under the Almoravid dynasty and Almohad Caliphate
The area of present-day Morocco has been inhabited since Paleolithic times, sometime between 190,000 and 90,000 BC
Mitochondrial DNA studies have discovered a close link between Berbers and the Saami of Scandinavia
Northwest Africa and Morocco were slowly drawn into the wider emerging Mediterranean world by the Phoenicians, who established trading colonies and settlements in the early Classical period
Morocco later became a realm of the Northwest African civilisation of ancient Carthage as part of its empire
Mauretania became a client kingdom of the Roman Empire in 33 BC
During the crisis of the 3rd century, parts of Mauretania were reconquered by Berber tribes
The Muslim conquest of the Maghreb, that started in the middle of the 7th century, was achieved by the Umayyad Caliphate early into the following century
The indigenous Berber tribes adopted Islam, but retained their customary laws
According to medieval legend, Idris ibn Abdallah had fled to Morocco after the Abbasids' massacre of his tribe in Iraq
From the 11th century onwards, a series of Berber dynasties arose

In 1549, the region fell to successive Arab dynasties claiming descent from the Islamic prophet, Muhammad: first the Saadi dynasty who ruled from 1549 to 1659, and then the Alaouite dynasty, who remain in power since the 17th century
Under the Saadi dynasty, the country repulsed Ottoman incursions and a Portuguese invasion at the battle of Ksar el Kebir in 1578
In 1631, Morocco was reunited by the Alaouite dynasty, who have been the ruling house of Morocco ever since
Morocco was the first nation to recognise the fledgling United States as an independent nation in 1777
As Europe industrialised, Northwest Africa was increasingly prized for its potential for colonisation
In 1904, France and Spain carved out zones of influence in Morocco

Between 1921 and 1926, a Berber uprising in the Rif Mountains, led by Abd el-Krim, led to the establishment of the Republic of the Rif
In 1943, the Istiqlal Party (Independence Party) was founded to press for independence, with discreet US support
France's exile of Sultan Mohammed V in 1953 to Madagascar and his replacement by the unpopular Mohammed Ben Aarafa sparked active opposition to the French and Spanish protectorates
Upon the death of Mohammed V, Hassan II became King of Morocco on 3 March 1961
The Spanish enclave of Ifni in the south was returned to Morocco in 1969
Moroccan and Algerian troops soon clashed in Western Sahara

Morocco has a coast by the Atlantic Ocean that reaches past the Strait of Gibraltar into the Mediterranean Sea

Morocco's capital city is Rabat; its largest city is its main port, Casablanca

The country's Mediterranean climate is similar to that of southern California, with lush forests in the northern and central mountain ranges of the country, giving way to drier conditions and inland deserts further southeast

In the Rif, Middle and High Atlas Mountains, there exist several different types of climates: Mediterranean along the coastal lowlands, giving way to a humid temperate climate at higher elevations with sufficient moisture to allow for the growth of different species of oaks, moss carpets, junipers, and Atlantic fir which is a royal conifer tree endemic to Morocco
Southeast of the Atlas mountains, near the Algerian borders, the climate becomes very dry, with long and hot summers

In contrast to the Sahara region in the south, coastal plains are fertile in the central and northern regions of the country, and comprise the backbone of the country's agriculture, in which 95% of the population live
In general, apart from the southeast regions (pre-Saharan and desert areas), Morocco's climate and geography are very similar to the Iberian peninsula
South of Agadir and east of Jerada near the Algerian borders, arid and desert climate starts to prevail

Due to Morocco's proximity to the Sahara desert and the North Sea of the Atlantic Ocean, two phenomena occur to influence the regional seasonal temperatures, either by raising temperatures by 7–8 degrees Celsius when sirocco blows from the east creating heatwaves, or by lowering temperatures by 7–8 degrees Celsius when cold damp air blows from the northwest, creating a coldwave or cold spell

Morocco has a wide range of biodiversity

The Moroccan Constitution provides for a monarchy with a Parliament and an independent judiciary
The constitution grants the king honorific powers; he is both the secular political leader and the "Commander of the Faithful" as a direct descendant of the Prophet Mohammed

The previous constitution of 1996 theoretically allowed the king to terminate the tenure of any minister, and after consultation with the heads of the higher and lower Assemblies, to dissolve the Parliament, suspend the constitution, call for new elections, or rule by decree
Since the constitutional reform of 1996, the bicameral legislature consists of two chambers

The Parliament's powers, though still relatively limited, were expanded under the 1992 and 1996 and even further in the 2011 constitutional revisions and include budgetary matters, approving bills, questioning ministers, and establishing ad hoc commissions of inquiry to investigate the government's actions

Culturally speaking, Morocco has always been successful in combining its Berber, Jewish and Arabic cultural heritage with external influences such as the French and the Spanish and, during the last decades, the Anglo-American lifestyles
The indigenous Berber people and a series of foreign invaders as well as religious and cultural influences have shaped Morocco's architectural styles
